Spot purchasers say loads of cheese are available. Demand for cheese is steady to lower in food service markets. Contacts report inflationary pressures are contributing to a decrease in retail cheese sales. Prices for cheese have declined in domestic markets. Export cheese demand is steady. Since last Tuesday, the price for cheese blocks have fallen on the CME by 8 cents. Some stakeholders say domestic loads of cheese are now being sold at a discount to loads produced internationally, and this may contribute to increased export demand in the coming weeks. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0500, and process cheese prices are down $0.1825. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance on contracts to sell 3.2 million pounds (1,472 metric tons) of American-type cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives who have contracts to sell 70.1 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 7.1 million pounds of cream cheese in export markets.

When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 930 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.

Staffing shortages and supply chain delays are preventing some production facilities from operating full schedules. Spot purchasers say that cheese inventories are available. Retail demand for cheese is unchanged. Food service demand for cheese is mixed. Some restaurants in the region are, reportedly, operating reduced hours and with limited menu offerings due to labor shortages and high input costs. Meanwhile, demand for mozzarella cheese is increasing from pizza makers who are preparing for increased purchasing from football fans. Export demand for cheese is steady. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0325, and process cheese prices are down $0.0250. Grade A Swiss prices are down $0.1000 this week.

The DMN Northeast July 2022 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.4515, compared to $2.6681 one month ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $2.2232, compared to $2.4574 one month ago.
secondary source info:
CME GROUP MONTHLY AVERAGES
The CME Group August monthly average price for barrels was $1.8741, compared to $2.0581 one month ago; blocks' average price was $1.8104, compared to $2.0143 one month ago.

EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance on contracts to sell 3.2 million pounds (1,472 metric tons) of American-type cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives who have contracts to sell 70.1 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 7.1 million pounds of cream cheese in export markets.

When combined with butter, AMF, cream cheese and whole milk powder, the program has assisted members with sales of 930 million pounds of milk on a milkfat basis.

commodity narrative:
Milk production continues to decline, seasonally, in the Northeast, though cheesemakers say they are running busy schedules. Staffing shortages and routine maintenance are causing some cheese plants to run below capacity. Cheese inventories continue to grow in the region. The NASS Cold Storage report released on August 22 showed a record high of total natural cheese in cold storage for July of this year. Some contacts suggest this report has contributed to bearishness in cheese markets. Since last Tuesday, market prices for barrels have fallen on the CME by $0.0675, while block prices slid $0.1200 lower. Retail demand for cheese is steady to lower, as higher food prices have caused some customers to reduce their cheese use. Food service demand is unchanged. Contacts say sales of cheese to international customers are steady. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0500, and process cheese prices are up $0.0625. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Cheesemakers in the Northeast say they are running busy schedules, despite seasonal declines in milk production. Some plants are operating below capacity due to staffing shortages. Cheese inventories are sturdy, and some stakeholders say their inventories are growing. Market prices for cheese in the $1.70s to $1.80s on the CME have, reportedly, contributed to increased demand from export customers. Stakeholders say increased demand is present from domestic purchasers as well. Despite this increased demand, contacts report retail and food service sales are down compared to last year. Some contacts say inflationary price pressures for businesses and consumers are contributing to decreased cheese purchasing. Amid stronger week to week demand for cheese, market prices for barrels have increased by 6.75 cents since last Tuesday. Meanwhile, block prices are up 7 cents in the same time frame. The price relationship between blocks and barrels remains inverted on the CME.

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0050, but process cheese prices are up $0.0550. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Amid strong regional production and softening demand, cheese inventories are building in the Northeast. Milk remains available for Class III operations, despite seasonal declines in farm level output. Cheese production is steady. Some plant managers report that staffing shortages are causing them to run below capacity. Demand for cheese continues to decline in both retail and food service markets. Contacts report retail demand is softening as higher prices have caused some grocery store shoppers to reduce their cheese use. Meanwhile, restauranteurs in the region say high input costs and staffing issues are causing them to reduce their operating hours and limit their menu items. CME prices for cheese barrels and blocks have fallen since last Tuesday. The block and barrel price relationship has inverted due to steeper declines in prices for blocks.

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0975, and process cheese prices are down $0.1050. Grade A Swiss prices are up by $0.0900 this week.

commodity narrative:
Steady milk supplies are clearing to Class III operations. Cheese stocks are sturdy. Some cheesemakers are reportedly cautious about continuing to grow inventories while demand is down across sectors, but production is fairly active for now. Market participants relay a slowdown in orders from retail outlets. Consumer demand is weaker amid inflationary pricing pressures. In response, some grocers are reducing order quantities and/or scaling back products offered. Food service demand is flat to down. Staffing issues and high input costs persist, and some eateries are limiting menu offerings and hours of service. Through Tuesday on the CME, prices for both blocks and barrels are trending upward with blocks eclipsing barrels on Monday. At the time of reporting, the price relationship remains restored. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.1275, and process cheese prices decreased $0.1475. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

Market participants relay a slowdown in orders from retail outlets. Consumer demand is weaker amid inflationary pricing pressures. In response, some grocers are reducing order quantities and/or scaling back products offered. Food service demand is flat to down. Staffing issues and high input costs persist, and some eateries are limiting menu offerings and hours of service. Through Tuesday on the CME, prices for both blocks and barrels are trending upward with blocks eclipsing barrels on Monday. At the time of reporting, the price relationship remains restored. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.1275, and process cheese prices decreased $0.1475. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Strong milk flows are clearing to Class III operations. For some plants, production schedules have been impacted by holiday downtime, labor pool issues, and/or supply chain shortages. Overall, however, cheesemaking remains generally active across the region. Manufacturers' inventories are bountiful, and cheese is reportedly available for spot and contract purchasing. While export interest continues to demonstrate strength, some market participants relay softening domestic demand across sectors. Retail sales are down as consumers face inflationary price pressures at the point of sale. Food service orders are weaker as well. On the CME this Tuesday, when the holiday-shortened trading week opened, prices for both blocks and barrels dropped. The block and barrel price relationship is, once again, inverted.

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0625, and process cheese prices increased $0.0150. Grade A Swiss prices are up $0.2250 this week.

The DMN Northeast June 2022 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.8199, compared to $2.9436 one month ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $2.5738, compared to $2.7065 one month ago.
secondary source info:

commodity narrative:
Milk is available for cheesemaking, and heavy milk volumes are flowing to Class III operations. Intakes are at, or near, capacity for some facilities. Northeastern plant managers are maintaining strong cheese production schedules. Regional cheese inventories are plentiful. Sustained hearty demand has kept supplies from becoming too heavy in recent months. Export demand remains good. However, domestic interest is showing some weakness across sectors. Grocery shoppers are facing higher prices at the checkout line, and retail cheese sales are trending lower. Some market participants also report softer food service demand. On the CME this Tuesday, when the holiday-shortened trading week opened, barrel prices inched higher while block prices dropped.  

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.1025, and process cheese prices are down $0.0800. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Milk is available for Northeastern Class III operations. Production is active in the region, although some cheesemaking facilities are operating at a reduced capacity due to supply chain issues and/or staffing shortages. Cheese inventories are sturdy. Some contacts say there is equilibrium between supply and demand for now, however, which is helping to prevent abundant cheese stocks from becoming burdensome. On international markets, U.S. cheese is priced competitively. Export demand is hearty. Retail cheese sales are flat to weaker. As inflationary pressures stretch budgets thin, some contacts speculate customers could be eliminating cheese from pared down grocery shopping lists over other staple items. Food service demand is steady to, in some areas, a little softer. Block and barrel prices have both slipped lower through Tuesday on the CME this week. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0200, but process cheese prices are down $0.0200. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Steady milk supplies are clearing to regional Class III operations. Northeastern cheese production is still busy, and milk intakes for some plants are at, or nearing, capacity. Inventories are plentiful and expanding, although persistent demand is helping to keep growth rates manageable. U.S. cheese prices are favorable on global markets, and export interest is hearty. Domestic sales are fairly stable. Retail orders are steady to softer. Food service demand remains firm overall, but some market participants are starting to relay hints of softness in some areas. Barrel prices have held steady through Tuesday on the CME this week, while block prices are trending higher. The price relationship has been restored, as blocks are once again outpricing barrels. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0625, and process cheese prices decreased $0.0325. Grade A Swiss prices increased $0.1750 this week.

The DMN Northeast May 2022 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.9436, compared to $2.8990 one month ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $2.7065, compared to $2.6519 one month ago.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern farm level milk output continues to climb, and milk is available for cheesemaking operations. Strong Class III milk intakes are supporting active regional cheese production schedules. Inventories are abundant. U.S. cheese prices are competitive on global markets, and export demand is said to be good. Stateside, as the summer grilling season has kicked off, some market participants are curious to see if grocery customers will begin to purchase more cheese for their cookouts. For now, however, retail sales remain flat to lower. Hearty food service cheese demand is holding firm. Block and barrel prices have been flip-flopping on the CME in recent weeks. After last week's volte-face, the block and barrel price relationship remains inverted. On this holiday-shortened trading week, block prices slid lower this Tuesday while barrel prices were unchanged.

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0575, and process cheese prices decreased $0.1025. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern farm level milk production is increasing, and milk is readily available for Class III operations. Cheese manufacturing remains active. Some plants are short-staffed and running under capacity, but production schedules are generally busy for mozzarella, provolone, and cheddar cheesemakers. Cheese inventories are satisfying hearty spot and contract demands, from both domestic and international customers. Retail sales are level. Food service orders are solid. Through Tuesday, prices for both blocks and barrels have pushed upward on the CME this week. The block and barrel price relationship remains inverted. Some contacts say demand for barrels is currently outpacing supply, and they surmise this imbalance is helping to keep barrel prices propped up, maintaining the block/barrel inversion. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0525, but process cheese prices increased $0.0375. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Steady to stronger milk supplies are clearing to Northeastern Class III operations this week. Some cheesemaking plants are back in action following a period of downtime. Regional cheese output is stable to higher. Some cheese plants are operating under reduced production capacities, however, as delays of production and/or packaging supplies and ongoing labor pool issues are limiting operations at some facilities. Steadily strong cheese demand, across sectors, is reportedly in good balance with sturdy inventories. Interest for U.S. cheese is healthy from international markets. Food service sales are firm. Retail is fairly stable, but some market participants note pockets of slightly softer demand. Through Tuesday on the CME, spot prices drifted lower for both blocks and barrels. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0200, and process cheese prices decreased $0.0150. Grade A Swiss prices are up $0.0600 this week.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern cheesemakers are maintaining active production schedules. Milk intakes are steady for Class III manufacturing plants. Cheese output is robust despite persistent staffing issues and supply chain snags that, in some cases, restrict operating capacity. Export interest is still strong, and domestic cheese demand is said to be good across sectors as well. Retail sales are healthy. Food service orders are stable to stronger; restaurant business is reportedly steadying for now, but remains hearty, after trending upward and rebounding earlier this year. On the CME this week, prices for both blocks and barrels fell on Monday but held firm Tuesday. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are unchanged, but process cheese prices decreased $0.0250. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

The DMN Northeast April 2022 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.8990, compared to $2.7156 one month ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $2.6519, compared to $2.3608 one month ago.

commodity narrative:
Regional farm level milk output is growing, and steady supplies are flowing to cheesemakers. Class III production is active. Some plants, however, are operating at a reduced capacity due to supply chain issues and labor shortages. Cheese manufacturers' inventories are generally plentiful. Market participants relay relatively unchanged demand, week to week, across sectors. Retail sales remain good on steadily strong consumer demand. Food service orders are level to higher. Export interest is hearty as U.S. cheese prices are favorable to international buyers. Through Tuesday on the CME this week, block prices have slipped lower while barrel prices pushed higher, inverting the price relationship once again. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0350, and process cheese prices decreased $0.0100. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Steady milk supplies are clearing to Class III operations. Production is busy for Northeastern cheesemakers. However, operating capacity for some cheesemaking plants is challenged by ongoing labor pool issues and shortages of trucks/drivers and production/packaging supplies. Additionally, a recent blast of wintery weather reportedly caused hazardous road conditions, contributing to some delivery delays. Cheese inventories are plentiful. U.S. prices are competitive on export markets, and global cheese demand is tenacious. Stateside, cheese sales are firm to higher, as well. Retail sales are good. Food service demand is stable to growing as the restaurant sector continues its rebound. Retail sales are good. On the CME this week through Tuesday, block and barrel price movement has been, cumulatively, downward. Despite this, Tuesday's prices remain above last week's average prices, and the inversion of the block and barrel price relationship persists. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0425, and process cheese prices increased $0.0875. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Class III milk intakes are strong as milk output slowly increases. Despite staffing shortages and supply chain interruptions of some production/packaging materials, Northeastern cheese plant managers are maintaining robust production schedules. Regional inventories are abundant, although market participants say steadily strong demand keeps supply levels manageable. Export interest is good; U.S. cheese prices remain favorable on global markets. Across domestic sectors, cheese sales are trending stable to stronger. Hearty demand is present from retail customers, and food service orders are steady to higher. On the CME, the block and barrel price relationship inverted last week as spot prices for both pushed past the $2.30 mark. Prices have held firm through Tuesday of this week.

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0625, and process cheese prices increased $0.0900. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.
secondary source info:
EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance to sell 3.9 million pounds (1,755 metric tons) of American-type cheese and 141,000 pounds (64 metric tons) of cream cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives with contracts to sell 40.4 million pounds of American-type cheeses and 4.1 million pounds of cream cheese.

commodity narrative:
Milk production continues to increase, and steady supplies are clearing to Northeastern Class III operations. Plant managers are keeping active cheese production schedules. Some dairy processing facilities continue to navigate labor issues, transportation bottlenecks, and/or supply shortages. Despite such challenges, cheese output is strong and regional inventories are sturdy. Export interest is reportedly good as global milk supplies remain tighter and U.S. cheese prices are favorable on international markets. Market participants report healthy cheese demand across domestic sectors as well. Retail sales are unchanged. While some variation exists from one locale to another, food service sales are generally level to improving. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0100, and process cheese prices increased $0.0350. Grade A Swiss prices are up $0.2250 this week.

The DMN Northeast March 2022 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.7156, compared to $2.4798 one month ago. Processed 5# sliced average price is $2.3608, compared to $2.1886 one month ago.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern cheese manufacturers are maintaining busy production schedules. Class III milk intakes are steady to increasing. Some cheesemaking plants are operating near capacity despite delivery delays, supply issues, and staffing shortages that continue to challenge dairy processing operations. Regional cheese inventories are plentiful. Industry contacts suggest sustained good demand prevents hearty supplies from becoming too onerous. U.S. cheese prices remain competitive on global markets, and export interest is robust. Domestic sales are stable to higher. Food service orders are steadily strong. Market participants say some limited-service eateries are meeting or surpassing pre-pandemic business levels, which is correlated with a boost in cheese consumption. Retail sales are unchanged; customer demand remains strong. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.1075, and process cheese prices increased $0.1650. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

Hearty demand from domestic and export markets is helping to keep abundant inventories from becoming burdensome. Retail sales are good. As COVID-related safety measures have dropped, recent reports indicate eatery patrons in some locations have been more eager to eat out while other cities are experiencing a slower rebound in dine-in traffic. Additionally, some full-service restaurants continue to offer reduced menu selections and/or hours of operation due to staffing and/or supply chain shortages.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern milk output is not increasing as quickly as some handlers had anticipated. Despite some reports of tighter spot milk availability, cheesemaking operations are generally receiving steady milk supplies and maintaining active production schedules. Steadily strong cheese demand, from domestic and export customers, is helping to moderate growth rates of manufacturers inventories and prevent abundant cheese stocks from feeling cumbersome. Retail sales are good. Some grocers are featuring cheese promotions in weekly circulars, and strong customer demand is moving plenty of units through checkout lines. Food service demand continues to pick up as many municipalities are relaxing or eliminating dine-in safety measures amidst foundering COVID case numbers. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0125, but process cheese prices decreased $0.0025. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

Regional cheese stocks are robust, but steady demand from domestic and export markets is reportedly helping to keep ample inventories from becoming burdensome. In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0325, and process cheese prices increased $0.0525. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

Some locales are dropping mask mandates and relaxing other COVID safety restrictions, and some market participants believe this may boost restaurant traffic. Cheddar block and barrel prices moved higher on the CME this week. The block and barrel price spread inverted late last week. On Tuesday, however, block pricing eclipsed barrel prices. The cheese market remains steady overall, but meandering prices are lending a slightly unsettled undertone. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0325, and process cheese prices increased $0.0525. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.

commodity narrative:
Milk is available for Northeastern Class III operations. Milk intakes for some cheesemaking facilities are at or near capacity. Plant managers are working to keep busy cheese production schedules throughout the region despite the challenges of staffing shortages, supply chain issues, and winter weather-related transportation delays. Cheese inventories are available for spot needs. Retail demand is sturdy as the end of the football season approaches. Food service orders are a little mixed. Sales from educational institutions are steadying. However, there are reportedly pockets of softening restaurant demand as dine-in traffic in some areas has wavered in recent weeks. On the CME Tuesday, both cheddar block and barrel prices dipped lower, but the block and barrel price spread remained inverted. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are down $0.0175, but process cheese prices increased $0.0650. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week.
secondary source info:
EXPORT ASSISTANCE
This week, a cooperative export assistance program accepted requests for export assistance to sell 2.2 million pounds (988 metric tons) of American-type cheese. So far this year, the program has assisted member cooperatives with contracts to sell 4.9 million pounds of American-type cheeses.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern cheesemakers are working through steady milk supplies. Cheese production schedules are busy. Some plant managers are reportedly running plants at full operating capacity, but production at some other facilities is impacted to varying degrees by labor issues. Cheese inventories are available to meet spot and contract needs. Coming off of a season of healthy holiday sales, customer cheese appetites are still strong. Retail orders are steady to growing ahead of an upcoming sporting event. Food service demand varies between locales, but the overall trend is steady. Cheddar block prices shifted higher on the CME through Tuesday of this week, while barrel prices held steady after dropping on Monday.

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0700, and process cheese prices increased $0.1400. Grade A Swiss prices are up $0.1450.

commodity narrative:
Northeastern cheesemakers are working through steady milk supplies. Cheese production schedules are busy. Some plant managers are reportedly running plants at full operating capacity, but production at some other facilities is impacted to varying degrees by labor issues. Cheese inventories are available to meet spot and contract needs. Coming off of a season of healthy holiday sales, customer cheese appetites are still strong. Retail orders are steady to growing ahead of an upcoming sporting event. Food service demand varies between locales, but the overall trend is steady. Cheddar block prices shifted higher on the CME through Tuesday of this week, while barrel prices held steady after dropping on Monday.

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0700, and process cheese prices increased $0.1400. Grade A Swiss prices are up $0.1450.

commodity narrative:
Steady milk supplies are clearing to Class III for Northeastern cheesemakers. Cheese production remains active. Some manufacturers are increasing output of Italian-type cheeses. Inventories are sizeable but not burdensome. Some market participants suggest there is equilibrium between abundant cheese supplies and persistent demand across sectors. Food service sales are fairly steady overall. However, orders are wavering in some locales where dine-in service is limited by staffing shortages, temporary COVID-related closures, and safety restrictions. Retail demand is steady to stronger. Costly transportation fees and limited truck availability in the Northeast are reportedly contributing to some delivery delays and other logistical challenges. Through Tuesday of this week on the CME group, barrel and cheddar block prices pushed upward. 

In the Northeast, wholesale cheese prices for both cheddar and Muenster are up $0.0825, and process cheese prices increased $0.0450. Grade A Swiss prices are unchanged this week. 

The DMN Northeast December 2021 monthly average price for cheddar blocks is $2.4698, compared to $2.3291 one month ago. The processed 5# sliced average price is $1.9652, compared to $1.9541 one month ago. For 2021, cheddar block prices averaged $2.3054 and processed 5# sliced prices averaged $1.9065.
secondary source info:
CME GROUP MONTHLY AVERAGES
The CME Group December 2021 monthly average price for barrels was $1.6548, compared to $1.5375 a month ago; the monthly average price for blocks was $1.8930, up from $1.7408 a month ago. For 2021, barrel prices averaged $1.5688 and block prices averaged $1.7140.
methodology: Information for the period January 3 - 7, 2022, issued weekly
